way for Protestant elites to reconsider ethnic, racial, and cultural difference. Using the manuscript collections and correspondence of leading American Protestants, as well the institutional records of various churches and religious organizations, Mislin offers insight into the historical constructions of faith and doubt, the interconnected relationship of secularism and pluralism, and the enormous influence of liberal Protestant thought on the political, cultural, and spiritual values of the twentieth-century United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aChristianity and other religionszUnited States. 0aLiberalism (Religion)xProtestant churchesxHistory. 0aProtestantismzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aReligious pluralismzUnited StatesxHistory. 4aReligious Studies. 4aU.S. History.  areligious pluralism, contemporary Protestantism, religious inclusivism, religious exclusivism, religious faith, religious traditions, nature of pluralism, transformative historical moment, American Protestant, liberal Protestant, secularism, urbanization, modern culture, American religious history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170143640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501701436423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501701436/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles